Twitter US Airline Sentiment¶

Context:¶

Twitter possesses 330 million monthly active users, which allows businesses to reach a broad population and connect with customers without intermediaries. On the other hand, there’s so much information that it’s difficult for brands to quickly detect negative social mentions that could harm their business.

That's why sentiment analysis/classification, which involves monitoring emotions in conversations on social media platforms, has become a key strategy in social media marketing.

Listening to how customers feel about the product/service on Twitter allows companies to understand their audience, keep on top of what’s being said about their brand and their competitors, and discover new trends in the industry.

However, this needs to be done periodically. Otherwise, the analysis will be stale and irrelevant. Also, it should be done for a well defined dataset - either segment tweets by geography or by demographic parameters. Otherwise, the computational effort will be high and the results will not be effective.

Also, analyzing the data sliced by airlines, reveals where a particular airline lags behind. This will help the management recognize and work on the areas of improvement.

Purpose:¶

The purpose of this analysis is to explore the numerous NLP features and build a classification model where we will be able to tag the tweets as positive or negative. Listening to how customers feel about the product/service on Twitter allows companies to understand their audience, keep on top of what’s being said about their brand and their competitors. We will also use word clouds to discover new trends in the industry.

Data description:¶

A sentiment analysis job about the problems of each major U.S. airline. Twitter data was scraped from February of 2015 and contributors were asked to first classify positive, negative, and neutral tweets, followed by categorizing negative reasons (such as "late flight" or "rude service").

Dataset:¶

The dataset has the following columns:

tweet_id
airline_sentiment
airline_sentiment_confidence
negativereason
negativereason_confidence
airline
airline_sentiment_gold
name
negativereason_gold
retweet_count
text
tweet_coord
tweet_created
tweet_location
user_timezone


text is the important field here. This is the target for NLP analysis and sentiment analysis.

def stacked_barplot(data, predictor, target):
    """
    Print the category counts and plot a stacked bar chart

    data: dataframe
    predictor: independent variable
    target: target variable
    """
    count = data[predictor].nunique()
    sorter = data[target].value_counts().index[-1]
    tab1 = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], margins=True).sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    print(tab1)
    print("-" * 120)
    tab = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], normalize="index").sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    tab.plot(kind="bar", stacked=True, figsize=(count + 5, 5))
    plt.legend(
        loc="lower left", frameon=False,
    )
    plt.legend(loc="upper left", bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1))
    plt.show()

Text Pre-processing:¶

  • Remove html tags.
  • Replace contractions in string. (e.g. replace I'm --> I am) and so on.
  • Remove numbers.
  • Make text lowercase.
  • Tokenization
  • To remove Stopwords.
  • Lemmatize text.

We will use the NLTK library to tokenize words, remove stopwords and lemmatize the remaining words

def strip_html(text):
    """Utility function to remove html tags from text"""
    soup = BeautifulSoup(text, "html.parser")                    
    return soup.get_text()

# remove html tags from text using the above defined function.
data['text'] = data['text'].apply(lambda x: strip_html(x))

def remove_numbers(text):
  """remove numbers from text"""
  text = re.sub(r'\d+', '', text)
  return text

# use above defined function to remove numerics from text
data['text'] = data['text'].apply(lambda x: remove_numbers(x))

customlist = ['not', "couldn't", 'didn', "didn't", 'doesn', "doesn't", 'hadn', "hadn't", 'hasn',
        "hasn't", 'haven', "haven't", 'isn', "isn't", 'ma', 'mightn', "mightn't", 'mustn',

        "wasn't", 'weren', "weren't", 'won', "won't", 'wouldn', "wouldn't"]
stopwords = list(set(z) - set(customlist))
In [34]:
# define utility clean up functions

lemmatizer = WordNetLemmatizer()

def remove_non_ascii(words):
    """Remove non-ASCII characters from list of tokenized words"""
    new_words = []
    for word in words:
        new_word = unicodedata.normalize('NFKD', word).encode('ascii', 'ignore').decode('utf-8', 'ignore')
        new_words.append(new_word)
    return new_words

def to_lowercase(words):
    """Convert all characters to lowercase from list of tokenized words"""
    new_words = []
    for word in words:
        new_word = word.lower()
        new_words.append(new_word)
    return new_words

def remove_punctuation(words):
    """Remove punctuation from list of tokenized words"""
    new_words = []
    for word in words:
        new_word = re.sub(r'[^\w\s]', '', word)
        if new_word != '':
            new_words.append(new_word)
    return new_words

def remove_stopwords(words):
    """Remove stop words from list of tokenized words"""
    new_words = []
    for word in words:
        if word not in stopwords:
            new_words.append(word)
    return new_words

def lemmatize_list(words):
    new_words = []
    for word in words:
      new_words.append(lemmatizer.lemmatize(word, pos='v'))
    return new_words

def normalize(words):
    words = remove_non_ascii(words)
    words = to_lowercase(words)
    words = remove_punctuation(words)
    words = remove_stopwords(words)
    words = lemmatize_list(words)
    return ' '.join(words)

def show_wordcloud(data, colname, title):
    """Show a word cloud using the WordCloud library"""
    text = ' '.join(data[colname].astype(str).tolist())                 # Converting Summary column into list
    stopwords = set(wordcloud.STOPWORDS)                                  # instantiate the stopwords from wordcloud
    
    fig_wordcloud = wordcloud.WordCloud(stopwords=stopwords,background_color='white',          # Setting the different parameter of stopwords
                    colormap='viridis', width=800, height=600).generate(text)
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(14,11), frameon=True)                             
    plt.imshow(fig_wordcloud)  
    plt.axis('off')
    plt.title(title, fontsize=30)
    plt.show()

Observations from the EDA:¶

  • There are 15 columns and about 15K rows.

  • tweet_id is the ID column and will play no role in modeling. text is the main field of interest as it contains the tweet content that will be used for NLP. airline_sentiment has the sentiment associated with the tweet. negativereason column has the reason for the negative sentiment and is available for tweets categorized as negative.

  • There are many blanks in many columns but none of them needs to be addressed as we don't use them in this analysis. Note that negativereason is blank for tweets that are neutral or positive. This is okay.

  • More than three fifth of tweets are categorized as negative. About a fifth are neutral. The rest are positive.

  • Among negative tweets, about a third are negative due to customer service issues. A fifth are related to delays.

  • More than a quarter of the tweets are about United airline. US Airways and American Airlines take up a fifth each. Virgin America has the least representation at 3.4%

  • Among the US timezones, Eastern time zone has the highest count followed by Central and Pacific respectively.

  • Virgin America has the least number of tweets, but has the biggest percentage positive tweets. Among the worst airlines, going by percentage positive tweets, are US Airways, American Airlines and United.

  • Looking at the negative tweet reason, Delta and United stand out, as their percentage of negative tweets that are about customer service issues, is not as high as the others. Delta seems to have a large percentage of tweets about late flights. United seems to be the worst as far as lost luggage is concerned.

  • Almost two third tweets have a 1.0 confidence on the sentiment value. Only about 37% of negative tweets have a reason confidence score of 1.0.

  • More than a third of all tweets have one or more numbers in the text.

  • Common words in the positive tweets are: thank, love, best, good, great, well. Common words in the negative tweets are: delay, bag, wait, call, time, customer service, gate, hold, baggage, seat, fix, rebooked, frustrate, cancel. The juxtaposition between the two categories is clear. Positive tweets are associated with good/warm/thankful feelings and the negative tweets are well, negative. The biggest issues that the negative tweets seem to be about are - delays and poor customer service.

# K-Fold Cross - validation
# "accuracy" is the chosen metric as it is the appropriate metric as we want to get both positive and negative classification right.
# f1 score would have been appropriate too.
cv_scores = []
base_ln = [x for x in range(1, 25)]
for b in base_ln:
    clf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators = b)
    scores = cross_val_score(clf, X_train, y_train, cv = 5, scoring = 'accuracy')
    cv_scores.append(scores.mean())
In [69]:
# plotting the error as k increases
error = [1 - x for x in cv_scores]                                 #error corresponds to each nu of estimator
optimal_learners = base_ln[error.index(min(error))]                #Selection of optimal nu of n_estimator corresponds to minimum error.
plt.plot(base_ln, error)                                           #Plot between each nu of estimator and misclassification error
xy = (optimal_learners, min(error))
plt.annotate('(%s, %s)' % xy, xy = xy, textcoords='data')
plt.xlabel("Number of base learners")
plt.ylabel("Misclassification Error")
plt.show()

Summary:¶

  • After the basic EDA, data pre-processing was done. This consisted of Html tag removal, Tokenization, Removing the numbers, Removal of Special Characters and Punctuations, Removal of stopwords, Conversion to lowercase and Lemmatizing.

  • Word clouds were produced to note the frequently used words in positive and negative tweets.

  • Sentiment analysis was done using simple Vader and TextBlob libraries.

  • After that, CountVectorizer and TfidfVectorizer were used and modeling was done. During this, vectorized column was used to fit the column. Cross-validation was done to ascertain model performance. Confusion matrices were made. Top 40 features were plotted as word clouds for both CountVectorizer and TfidfVectorizer.

Conclusion:¶

  • The EDA phase revealed a few insights. The majority of tweets were negative hinting at the fact that more people tweet about negative experiences than positive. Unhappiness with Customer service is the leading cause of negative tweets. Airlines being a retail customer service, improving customer service should improve the sentiment about the airlines.

  • Smaller niche players seem to have better percentage positive tweets as compared to larger airlines. While the cause behind this is not known from this dataset, the larger airlines should look into the customer service experience with the small airlines and scout for areas of improvement.

  • Delta seems to have a severe issue with late flights, while United seems to have a problem with checked-in bags.

  • The Word cloud for positive and negative tweets are as distinct and clear as night and day! The management of airlines should track these words and look for improvement areas and strengthen what is going well already.

  • Vader and TextBlob tools performed relatively poorly. Vader had an accuracy of 57%. A huge numbers of tweets that were negative but Vader prediction was positive. TextBlob also performed poorly (accuracy 54%) and it had the same misclassification problem as Vader.

  • With CountVectorizer, the best model had an accuracy of 78%. Misclassifications were fewer.

  • TfidfVectorizer's best model also had an accuracy of 78% with a small percentage of misclassifications.

  • Top 40 word clouds for these two, had many words in common. This is expected.

  • With both CountVectorizer and TfidfVectorizer, neutral tweets were misclassified as positive or negative. This suggests that there is room for further improvement in these algorithms. These misclassified tweets can be investigated to help improve model building in the future.
